      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Recipe protection (Making Books column, June 29) begins long before ingredients are typeset.</p>
        <p>My 18 years as a professional chef left me with one nagging question. At a time when half the world is starving, what's the reasoning for not sharing the recipe (or demonstrating the technique) for preparing, say, a veal reduction sauce with a hint of thyme?</p>
        <p>Near the end of my studies at the Culinary Institute of America, a chef instructor provided advice that sustained me through my career. ''Steal with your eyes,'' he said.</p>
        <p>These words proved more valuable than any five-pound cookbook with glossy photographs unable to weather a kitchen's strain.</p>
        <p>But for those who view the culinary arts as a profession, it is Julia Child's remarks that will outlast lawyers arguing plagiarism. As she put it, reproducing a recipe, in any form, is a compliment.</p>
        <p>ROBERT REMLER  Port Washington, N.Y., June 29, 2000</p>
      </block>
